The famous Blue Lagoon in Iceland 🤍
@retreat.bluelagoon @bluelagoonis
#BlueLagoonSkincare 
#BlueLagoonIceland

all your iceland questions answered :)

Everything in Iceland is far apart- we drove at least 3-4 hours a day sometimes more. You definitely need to rent a car or book a driver/tour guide through your hotel. Since we were a big group we had a sprinter van which was nice because we could leave extra layers jackets/shoes in the car. The weather can change really fast and you always need a change of clothes. Be prepared to get wet and dirty.

Where we stayed:
The Edition in Reykjavik 
Retreat at Blue Lagoon (about an hour from Reykjavik)
Dalur Lake House (about an hour from Reykjavik)
Deplar Farm (5-6 hours from Reykjavik)

Things we did:
Dinner at Grillmarkaðurinn in Reykjavik
Drinks at Tipsy in Reykjavik
Late night hotdog stand in Reykjavik
Ice snowmobiling at Langjokull Glacier
Seljalandsfoss, Skogafoss and Gulfoss waterfalls
Diving/ snorkeling at Silfra fissure
Hiking Katla ice caves
Whale watching and paddle boarding in Dalvik
Fish soup restaurant in Dalvik
Horseback riding 
Hot springs - Blue Lagoon, Sky Lagoon, Hvammsvik
& the long drives alone and the scenery and landscape are just as special.

there’s so many more things we didn’t have time to do. a week is certainly not enough time to explore all of Iceland. We wanted to do a volcano tour and white water rafting - so that’s for next time. :)

& the number one question- how to see the northern lights: there’s a website that you can check to see what the chances are each night. Supposedly it’s best from sept- march. It can happen for just a few minutes, longer, or obviously not at all. We were told our chances to see them were very low and even the website said 2/10. The hotel told us they hadn’t seen them in weeks, so I guess we got really lucky. The sky has to be really dark and clear. It happened around 2am. It was definitely the highlight of the trip- i think we all cried a bit at the magic.

Wow! It is an honor to be recognized by @forbes as one of the top creators in the world, and especially to be acknowledged for the entrepreneurship of my career and my brands. An as OG in the space, over the past decade+ I have watched the digital landscape evolve into a place where being a digital entrepreneur/ creator is a respected and admired career form. It definitely wasn’t always this way. I’ve watched many of my peers build global empires and continue to push the boundaries as to what is possible for anyone. It certainly has inspired countless dreams and has turned this industry into arguably one of the most influential and powerful spaces of our time. I’m proud to have made a least a small impact. Thank you @forbes for including me on your prestigious Top Creators list and thank you to all of you :)
